 Shriver]] || Television movie\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[In Her Line of Fire]]'' || Lynn Delaney ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Between Truth and Lies]]'' || Dr. Claire Parker ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Nanking (2007 film)|Nanking]]'' || Minnie Vautrin ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Law & Order]]'' || Ashley Jones || Episode: \"Remains of the Day\"\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[The Golden Boys]]'' || Martha ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[My Suicide]]'' || Charlotte Silver ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Ay Lav Yu]]'' || Pamela ||\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Rise of the Zombies]]'' || Dr. Lynn Snyder || Television movie\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Running from Crazy]]'' || Herself || Television documentary\n|-\n| 2014 || |''[[Unity (film)|Unity]]'' || Herself (as Narrator) || Documentary\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Papa: Hemingway in Cuba]]'' || Woman Guest || \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Finding Fortune]]'' || Madison || Television movie \n|-\n|}\n\n== Works ==\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | authormask = ---\n | title = Finding My Balance: A Memoir\n | titlelink = Asana#In culture\n | year = 2002\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = Simon & Schuster\n | isbn = 0-7432-3807-9\n | url-access = registration\n | url = https://archive.org/details/findingmybalance00mari\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | authormask = ---\n | title = Mariel Hemingway's Healthy Living from the Inside Out: Every Woman's Guide to Real Beauty, Renewed Energy, and a Radiant Life\n | year = 2006\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = HarperOne\n | isbn = 978-0-06-089039-1\n | url-access = registration\n | url = https://archive.org/details/marielhemingways00hemi\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | authormask= --- \n | title = MARIEL'S KITCHEN Simple Ingredients for a Delicious and Satisfying Life\n | year = 2009\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = HarperOne\n | isbn = 978-0-06-164987-5\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | authormask= --- \n | title = Running With Nature\n | year = 2013\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = Changing Lives Press\n | isbn = 0988247615\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | author1mask= --- \n | author2=Greenman, Ben\n | lastauthoramp=yes\n | title = Out Came the Sun: Overcoming the Legacy of Mental Illness, Addiction, and Suicide in My Family\n | year = 2013\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = Regan Arts\n | isbn = 1941393233\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Hemingway\n | first = Mariel\n | authormask= --- \n | title = Invisible Girl\n | year = 2015\n | edition = 1st\n | publisher = Regan Arts\n | isbn = 978-1941393-24-6\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mariel Hemingway}}\n* {{IMDb name|446}}\n* {{AllRovi name|93989}}\n* [http://www.marielhemingway.com/ Mariel Hemingway.com] \u2013 official website for Mariel's book ''Healthy Living''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hemingway, Mariel}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from California]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Idaho]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hemingway family]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mental health activists]]\n[[Category:Nautilus Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Ketchum, Idaho]]\n[[Category:People from Mill Valley, California]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image          = Mariel Hemingway headshot, free use.jpg\n| caption        = Hemingway in 2011\n| birth_name     = Mariel Hadley Hemingway\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1961|11|22}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mill Valley, California]], U.S.\n| residence      = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| occupation     = Actress, writer\n| years_active   = 1976\u2013present\n| alma_mater     = [[Boston University]]\n| spouse         = {{marriage|Stephen Crisman<br>|1984|2009|end=div}}\n| children       = [[Dree Hemingway|Dree Crisman]]<br>[[Langley Fox]]\n| parents        = [[Jack Hemingway]]<br>Byra Louise Whittlesey\n| relatives      = [[Ernest Hemingway]] <br><small>(paternal grandfather)</small><br>[[Margaux Hemingway]] <small>(sister)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Mariel Hadley Hemingway''' (born November 22, 1961) is an American actress. She began acting at age 14 with a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]]\u2013nominated breakout role in ''[[Lipstick (1976 film)|Lipstick]]'' (1976), and received [[Academy Awards|Academy]] and [[BAFTA Award]] nominations for her performance in [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Manhattan (film)|Manhattan]]'' (1979).\n\nShe is also known for her leading roles in  ''[[Personal Best (film)|Personal Best]]'' (1982) and ''[[Star 80]]'' (1983), as well as in the TV series ''[[Civil Wars (TV series)|Civil Wars]]'', for which she received a Golden Globe nomination. Amid [[Mental disorder|mental health]] struggles, Hemingway's career dwindled in the 1990s. She has starred in and co-produced videos about [[Yoga as exercise|yoga]] and holistic living. She published a yoga memoir, ''[[Asana#In culture|Finding My Balance]]'', in 2002, and another more general one, ''Out Came the Sun'', in 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nHemingway was born in [[Mill Valley, California]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/mariel_h_hemingway_born_1961_7643792|title=Mariel H Hemingway was born on November 22, 1961 in Marin County, California|publisher=californiabirthindex.org|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref> the third daughter of Byra Louise (n\u00e9e Whittlesey) Hemingway (1922\u20131988) and [[Jack Hemingway]] (1923\u20132000), a writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/98/Mariel-Hemingway.html|title=Mariel Hemingway profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> Her sisters are Joan Hemingway (born 1950) and [[Margaux Hemingway]] (1954\u20131996). Margaux, who was an actress and model, died of a [[phenobarbital|barbiturate]] overdose at age 42 in 1996.\n\nHer paternal grandparents were [[Hadley Richardson]] (1891\u20131979) and [[Nobel Prize]]\u2013laureate novelist [[Ernest Hemingway]] (1899\u20131961), who committed suicide four months before she was born. She was named for the Cuban port of [[Mariel, Cuba|Mariel]]\u2014her father and grandfather visited the village regularly to go fishing. Her middle name was her paternal grandmother's. Hemingway grew up primarily in [[Ketchum, Idaho]], where her father lived, and where Ernest had spent time as a sportsman and writer.\n\n==Career in film==\nHemingway's first role was with her real-life sister [[Margaux Hemingway|Margaux]] (also in her debut role) in the film ''[[Lipstick (1976 film)|Lipstick]]'' (1976), in which they played sisters. She received notice for her acting and was nominated as \"Best Newcomer\" for the [[Golden Globe Award]] that year. Her highest profile role came with her role in [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Manhattan (film)|Manhattan]]'' (1979), a [[romantic comedy]] in which she plays Tracy, a high school student and Allen's lover. Just 16 during filming (in the film she is said to be 17), she was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=\"JulieMiller\">{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Julie |title=Mariel Hemingway Says Woody Allen Tried to Seduce Her When She Was a Teenager |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/03/woody-allen-mariel-hemingway-manhattan |accessdate=4 January 2020 |publisher=Vanity Fair |date=March 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn her memoir, ''Out Came The Sun'' (2015), Hemingway alleged that Allen attempted to begin a sexual relationship with her shortly after filming was completed, when she had turned 18. Hemingway declined his advances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/03/hemingway-says-woody-allen-tried-to-seduce-her.html|title=Mariel Hemingway Says Woody Allen Tried to Seduce Her at 18|work=Vulture|publisher=New York Media|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015|author=Fitz-Gerald, Sean}}</ref><ref>Howard Kurtz [http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2015/03/25/exclusive-young-mariel-hemingway-had-to-rebuff-woody-allens-advances \"Exclusive: Young Mariel Hemingway had to rebuff Woody Allen's advances\"], Fox News, March 25, 2015.</ref><ref>Helen Nianias [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/woody-allen-mariel-hemingway-granddaughter-of-writer-ernest-claims-director-had-crush-on-her-when-she-was-17-10135298.html \"Woody Allen: Mariel Hemingway, granddaughter of writer Ernest, claims director had 'crush' on her when she was 17\"], ''The Independent'', March 26, 2015.</ref> <ref name=\"JulieMiller\" />\n\nIn ''[[Personal Best (film)|Personal Best]]'' (1982), she played a [[bisexuality|bisexual]] [[track and field|track-and-field]] athlete in a film noted for its [[lesbian]] love scenes. In connection with ''Personal Best'', she appeared in a nude pictorial in the April 1982 issue of ''[[Playboy]]'' and was on the cover.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n[[File:Mariel Hemingway by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|Hemingway in April 2017]]\n\nShe starred as [[Dorothy Stratten]] in ''[[Star 80]]'' (1983), a film about the ''Playboy'' model's life and murder. Reports circulated for years that Hemingway had had her breasts enlarged to play the role of Stratten, but during a 2007 appearance on the late-night [[Talk show|talk]] and [[variety show]], ''[[Fashionably Late with Stacy London]]'', she said she had had the surgery before ''Star 80''. Her [[breast implants]] were removed years later after they had ruptured.<ref>Hemingway, Mariel. ''Finding My Balance''. New York: Simon & Schuster, 2003.<!-- ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nShe was featured in ''[[Superman IV: The Quest for Peace]]'' (1987) as Lacy Warfield. Subsequently, released additional footage showed an expansion of her role. She also co-starred in the 1991\u201393 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series ''[[Civil Wars (TV series)|Civil Wars]]''. She was cast as the female lead in Darren Star's CBS drama ''[[Central Park West (TV series)|Central Park West]]'' for the 1995-96 season; however, the show fared poorly with both critics and viewers, and after 13 episodes Hemingway was told that the show wanted her to accept a huge pay cut and demotion to recurring character status. She quit the series, which only lasted eight more episodes before being cancelled. In 1996, she had a leading role in the British TV movie ''September'', playing the wife of [[Michael York]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nShe has played a lesbian or bisexual woman in several films and television shows, including ''Personal Best'', ''[[The Sex Monster]]'', ''[[In Her Line of Fire]]'', and episodes of the TV series ''[[Roseanne]]'' (\"[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell (Roseanne)|Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]\" and \"[[December Bride (Roseanne)|December Bride]]\") and ''[[Crossing Jordan]]''. Hemingway, however, is not gay. She has said she formed a \"big connection with the gay and lesbian community\" after ''Personal Best'' and enjoys taking roles in \"cutting-edge\" productions.<ref>MacDonald, Jay (May 1, 2007). [http://www.bankrate.com/brm/news/investing/20070501_fame_fortune_mariel_hemingway_a1.asp \"Fame & Fortune: Mariel Hemingway\"], ''[[Bankrate]]''; accessed August 27, 2009.</ref>\n\nShe is currently the host of ''Spiritual Cinema'',{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} a monthly television show dedicated to spiritual films. She has begun hosting a series of [[yoga as exercise|yoga]] practice videos ''Yoga Now'', with [[guru]] [[Rodney Yee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.probidad.org/ebooks/5629-yoga-now-accelerated-workout-dvd-.html|title=Yoga Now: Accelerated Workout DVD|work=probidad.org|quote=Longtime yoga practitioner and Hollywood actress Mariel Hemingway teams up with renowned instructor Rodney Yee  ... through a combination of yoga, cardio, and proper eating habits|accessdate=November 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909212403/http://www.probidad.org/ebooks/5629-yoga-now-accelerated-workout-dvd-.html|archive-date=September 9, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHemingway worked on the documentary film ''[[Running from Crazy]]'', directed by [[Barbara Kopple]] and produced by the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]] chronicling the Hemingway family's history of suicide, substance abuse and mental illness,<ref>[http://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/mariel-hemingway-bio Mariel Hemingway Bio], ''Town & Country Magazine''; accessed September 26, 2016.</ref> shown at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2013. In October 2013, Hemingway received a humanitarian award from the [[San Diego Film Festival]] for her role in the documentary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.10news.com/news/actress-mariel-hemingway-honored-with-humanitarian-award-at-san-diego-film-festival-10062013|title=Actress Mariel Hemingway honored with humanitarian award at San Diego Film Festival|work=10News|accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHemingway married Stephen Crisman. Together, they had two daughters, [[Dree Hemingway]] and [[Langley Fox]]. They separated in 2008 and divorced the following year.<ref>{{cite web|author=My New Life|url=http://www.marielhemingway.com/blog/2008/12|title=Mariel Hemingway's Personal Journal &#124; Living a Holistic Life|publisher=Marielhemingway.com|date=December 7, 2008|accessdate=March 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320075800/http://www.marielhemingway.com/blog/2008/12/|archivedate=March 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/27/magazine/the-importance-of-not-being-ernest.html ''The New York Times'' profile], nytimes.com; accessed September 26, 2016.<br>NOTE: IMDb entry for Stephen Crisman says they are still married; Hemingway's indicates they divorced in 2009.<br>''The New York Times'' says the couple divorced in 2008.</ref>\n\nAs of early 2011, Hemingway was romantically linked with former stuntman Bobby Williams, with whom she has co-authored a self-help book.<ref>{{cite news|author=Strobel, Mike|url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/columnists/mike_strobel/2011/01/29/17084286.html|title=The moon also rises on Mariel Hemingway|newspaper=Toronto Sun|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref> In April 2015, Williams was described as Hemingway's partner.<ref name=\"yahoo4/15\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Bobbi|title=How Mariel Hemingway Overcame Her Family's Tragic Legacy|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/how-mariel-hemingway-overcame-her-family-s-tragic-legacy-185047938.html|website=Yahoo! News|date=April 6, 2015|quote=I meditate every day, twice a day. I think if you learn to do TM, it changes your life|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> She practices [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]].<ref name=\"yahoo4/15\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Semmes|first1=Anne|title=Mariel Hemingway shares stories of a troubled family|url=http://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Mariel-Hemingway-shares-stories-of-a-troubled-6193101.php|accessdate=May 17, 2015|date=April 11, 2015|quote=I do (transcendental) meditation twice a day.}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2013 television documentary film, ''[[Running from Crazy]]'',<ref name=running>{{cite AV media|people=Kopple, Barbara|date=January 7, 2013|title=Running from Crazy|medium=Motion picture|location=United States|publisher=Oprah Winfrey Network}}</ref> Hemingway, then 51, talked of her bouts of [[mental illness]] and her still lingering issues with her siblings.<ref name=wpost/><ref name=cnn/> She spoke of her family's struggles with alcoholism, mental illnesses and suicide. (In particular she mentioned how her sister Margaux's suicide continued to haunt her.)<ref name=wpost/><ref name=cnn/> She also made claims that her parents' marriage was abusive and unhappy, and about abusive incidents in her childhood.{{efn|She states in the documentary: \"When I was really small, and I shared a room with Margaux, and my dad came in the room, you know... I don't wanna call it what it was, but it wasn't right, you know... um, it's hard to have a visual of that, you don't wanna see your dad doing those things, but I know it, I know it happened. I think that my dad abused the girls [Margaux and Joan], sexually abused the girls, um, when they were young. My dad, if you met him, was not, you don't think 'oh, pedophile', or this or that, you just didn't, that's not what came to your mind at all, at all, he was a beautiful man and in many ways, but I think it happened in drunk, you know, behavior, you know 'my wife doesn't love me', I don't know what the reasons were. You know 'I'm obsessed with my daughters', I don't know why a person can even go there.... I know people would say, 'there's no way in hell your father did that'. And yet, Margaux was obsessed with him, Muffet was obsessed with him, and my mother allowed me to sleep with her my whole childhood practically. I slept with my mom from age seven to age sixteen. But I witnessed it as a kid, so... that's why I thought it never happened to me, because... I don't know why it didn't, but I just assumed it happened to them and it didn't happen to me.\"<ref name=running/>}}<ref name=wpost>{{cite web|first=Hank|last=Stuever|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/owns-running-from-crazy-when-you-hear-those-bells-they-dont-always-toll-for-thee/2014/04/24/3e641ac6-c973-11e3-a75e-463587891b57_story.html|title=OWN's 'Running From Crazy': When you hear those bells, they don\u2019t always toll for thee|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 26, 2014|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite web|first=Elizabeth|last=Landau|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/01/21/health/hemingway-film|title=Hemingway family mental illness explored in new film|work=[[CNN]]|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1976 || ''[[Lipstick (1976 film)|Lipstick]]'' || Kathy McCormick || Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actress]]\n|-\n| 1976 || ''[[I Want to Keep My Baby]]'' || Sue Ann Cunningham || Television movie\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Manhattan (film)|Manhattan]]'' || Tracy || Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Personal Best (film)|Personal Best]]'' || Chris Cahill ||\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Star 80]]'' || [[Dorothy Stratten]] ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Creator (film)|Creator]]'' || Meli ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[The Mean Season]]'' || Christine Connelly ||\n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Amerika (miniseries)|Amerika]]'' || Kimberly Ballard || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Superman IV: The Quest for Peace]]'' || Lacy Warfield || Nominated\u2014[[Razzie Award for Worst Supporting Actress]]\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Steal the Sky]]'' || Helen Mason || Television movie\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Sunset (1988 film)|Sunset]]'' || Cheryl King || Nominated\u2014[[Razzie Award for Worst Supporting Actress]]\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Delirious (1991 film)|Delirious]]'' || Janet Dubois/Louise ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]'' || Miranda Singer || Episode: \"Loved to Death\"\n|-\n| 1991\u201393 || ''[[Civil Wars (TV series)|Civil Wars]]'' || Sydney Guilford || 36 episodes<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama]]\n|-\n| 1992 || ''[[Falling from Grace (film)|Falling from Grace]]'' || Alice Parks ||\n|-\n| 1993 || ''[[Desperate Rescue: The Cathy Mahone Story]]''